Set $\tan A = x,$ $\tan B = y.$ Since $\tan \alpha \tan \beta = \dfrac{\sin \alpha \sin \beta}{\cos \alpha \cos \beta} = \dfrac{\sin \alpha \sin \beta}{-\sin (\alpha + \beta)} = -\dfrac{\sin \alpha \sin \beta}{-\sin (\pi - (\alpha + \beta))} = -\dfrac{\sin \alpha \sin \beta}{\sin (\alpha + \beta)} = -\dfrac{xy}{x + y},$ $\tan A \tan B = -\dfrac{xy}{x + y}.$</think> $CH \cdot HF = 6 \cdot 15 = 90 = CF^2$, so $CF = 3\sqrt{10}$. Let $H_1$ be the foot of the altitude from $A$ to $\overline{BC}$, and $H_2$ be the foot of the altitude from $B$ to $\overline{AC}$. Then $CH_1H_2F$ is a rectangle. By the Pythagorean Theorem and the similarity of triangles, \[\dfrac{HF}{H_1H_2} = \dfrac{CF}{CH_1} \implies H_1H_2 = \dfrac{HF}{CF} \cdot CH_1 = \dfrac6{3\sqrt{10}} \cdot 15 = 3\sqrt{10}.\]Thus, $H_1H_2 = CH_2$ so $H$ is the midpoint of $\overline{CH_2}$. Hence, $\triangle CH_1H \sim \triangle CBF$ so $\overline{CH_1}$ bisects $\overline{BF}$, and $HF_2 = FH_1$, so $BF_1 = HF_2 = 9$. Since $CF_1 \parallel AH$ and $H$ is the midpoint of $\overline{BF}$, $HF = BH$, so $\triangle BFH$ is isosceles, and therefore $\angle BHF = \angle FBH \implies \tan \angle BHF = \tan \angle FBH \implies HF_2 = BF_1 = 9 \implies \overline{BF} = 18$. Since $\tan 90^\circ + \angle CAB = \tan 180^\circ$, we have that $\tan A \tan B = -\dfrac{xy}{x + y} = \boxed{-\dfrac{5}{12}}$.</think>
